#Create a CI pipeline using GitHub Actions to build and push a Docker image of a Python app to Docker Hub

Step 1 – Create project files

Your project folder should look like this:

python-app/
│
├── app.py
├── requirements.txt
├── Dockerfile
└── .github/
    └── workflows/
        └── docker-publish.yml
1. Create app.py
from flask import Flask

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return "<h1>Python App running from Docker image!</h1>"

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)
2. Create requirements.txt
flask
3. Create Dockerfile
FROM python:3.11-slim

WORKDIR /app

COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

COPY . .

EXPOSE 5000

CMD ["python", "app.py"]
Step 2 – Create workflow file

Create folder and file:

mkdir .github
mkdir .github\workflows
notepad .github\workflows\docker-publish.yml

Paste this code:

name: Build and Push Docker Image

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main ]

jobs:
  build-push:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout code
        uses: actions/checkout@v3

      - name: Log in to Docker Hub
        uses: docker/login-action@v3
        with:
          username: ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}
          password: ${{ secrets.DOCKER_PASSWORD }}

      - name: Build Docker image
        run: docker build -t ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/python-app:latest .

      - name: Push to Docker Hub
        run: docker push ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/python-app:latest

Save and close the file.

Step 3 – Add secrets to GitHub

Open your GitHub repository.

Go to:

Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions

Click New repository secret and add these two secrets:

Secret 1
Name: DOCKER_USERNAME
Value: your Docker Hub username
Secret 2
Name: DOCKER_PASSWORD
Value: your Docker Hub access token

Example:

DOCKER_USERNAME = deyona
DOCKER_PASSWORD = dckr_pat_xxxxxxxxxxxxxx
Step 4 – Create Docker Hub access token

Open Docker Hub.

Go to:

Account Settings → Security → New Access Token

Create a token and copy it.

Use that token as the value of DOCKER_PASSWORD.

Step 5 – Push project to GitHub

Open terminal in your project folder and run:

git init
git add .
git commit -m "Add Python app and GitHub Actions CI pipeline"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/<your-repo>.git
git pull origin main --allow-unrelated-histories
git push origin main

If remote is already added, skip the git remote add origin command.

Step 6 – Trigger the workflow

Whenever you push to main, the workflow starts automatically.

If needed, create an empty commit to trigger it:

git commit --allow-empty -m "trigger workflow"
git push origin main
Step 7 – Check GitHub Actions output

Open your GitHub repository and click:

Actions

You should see:

Build and Push Docker Image

Possible results:

yellow = running
green = success
red = failed
Step 8 – Check Docker Hub

After successful workflow run, open Docker Hub.

You should see this image:

<your-dockerhub-username>/python-app:latest

Example:

deyona/python-app:latest
Step 9 – Pull and run the image locally
docker pull <your-dockerhub-username>/python-app:latest
docker run -d -p 5000:5000 --name pythonapp <your-dockerhub-username>/python-app:latest

Open in browser:

http://localhost:5000

Output:

Python App running from Docker image!
